            <div class="ins_notes">
                <span class="note" id="note-1"><a href="#ref-1">[1]</a> This is the second in a series of five extant inscriptions honouring ephebes in the period between Sulla and Augustus. See <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/1039"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1039</a>. Preserved are decrees honouring the superintendent of the ephebes (<i>kosmetes</i>) and honouring the ephebes themselves and their tutors and trainers. We can infer from the other surviving inscriptions that these will have been preceded by a decree honouring the ephebes and their superintendent for their performance of sacrifices. They may have been followed on the stone by a roster of the ephebes. Note that unlike the first in the series, <i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1039, passed in 79/8 BC, these are not decrees of the Council alone, but probouleumatic decrees of the Assembly (on decrees of the Council and People in this period see <a href="/inscription/IRhamn/423" class="highlight"><i>I&nbspRhamnous</i> 423</a> with notes). The monument was probably set up originally in the Agora, cf. <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/1039"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1039</a> n. 4. <br/><br/><strong>Textual Note</strong>: Our text follows <i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1041 with minor adjustments to dots and square brackets based on autopsy by Schneider in 2019, in addition to the following changes: 10–11 προσεδ[ρε]|[ύοντες ταῖς τῶν -ων σχολαῖς] <i>IG</i>, φιλοσόφων M. Haake <i>Der Philosoph in der Stadt</i> (2007), 49 n. 155 | 30-31 Μ̣ε|[νίσκον] Raubitschek (<i>SEG</i> 17.33), [Π]ε- <i>IG</i> | At the end the position of the surviving crown suggests that there were two further crowns to the left of it. Also, the rubric οἱ ἔφ[ηβ]οι τὸν κ[οσ]μητήν is inscribed above not within (as <i>IG</i>) the crown. The name of the <i>kosmetes</i> will have been inscribed within the crown. For photographic documentation see <a class="highlight" href="https://www.atticinscriptions.com/papers/aio-papers-11b"><i>AIO Papers</i> 11B</a>.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-2"><a href="#ref-2">[2]</a> On the image, probably a painted image of his bust on a shield (an <i>eikon en hoplo</i> or <i>imago clipeata</i>), a common honour in the 1st century BC, see  <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/SEG/2895"><i>SEG</i> 28.95</a> with notes.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-3"><a href="#ref-3">[3]</a> The archonship of Polycharmos of Azenia is dated to 44/3 BC (Byrne, <a class="highlight" href="http://www.athnames.org/P-U.html"><i>Athenian Onomasticon</i></a>, s.v.) or 43/2 BC (Follet, <i>REG</i> 118, 2005, 13). He was perhaps the general Polycharmos (“Polycharmo praetore”) who was mentioned by Cicero <i>Ad Att.</i> 5.11.6 and <i>Ad Fam.</i> 13.1.5 (see E. Rawson, <i>Athenaeum</i> 63, 52–53 [<i>SEG</i> 35.242]). Like other decrees of this type they will have been passed in the year following the completion of the ephebes’ year of service.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-4"><a href="#ref-4">[4]</a> The sailing of the ephebes from Athens to the island of <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/580101">Salamis</a> took place as part of the festival Aianteia and sacrifices to Zeus Tropaios which were celebrated on Salamis to commemorate the victory of 480 BC against the Persians (see Pélékidis, <i>Histoire de l’éphebie attique</i>, 1962, 247–49; <a class="highlight" href="/browse/bysource/ParkerPoly/">Parker, <i>Polytheism</i></a>, 456; on Athenian interest in Salamis in the post-Sullan period see <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/AIO/2439"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1035</a>, ll. 30-35 with notes).</span>
<span class="note" id="note-5"><a href="#ref-5">[5]</a> The Ptolemaion was one of the city’s gymnasia and held a significant library, as various dedications of books by ephebes testify: in E. Perrin-Saminadayar, <i>Éducation, Culture et Société à Athènes</i> (2007) T30, ll. 31-32 (<i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1009, 7-8) the ephebes of 117/6 BC dedicated 100 books for the library, "first (i.e. for the first time?) in accordance with the decree which Theodorides of <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/580062">Piraeus</a> proposed"; in <i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1029 (Perrin T33), ll. 25-26, the ephebes of 97/6 BC dedicated 100 books for the library of the Ptolemaion "in accordance with the decree". <i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1030 (Perrin T34), l. 36, ca. 98/7 BC, has restored text similar to T33, mentioning the decree of Theodorides. Here the dedication of books is apparently said to be in accordance with the decree which Metrophanes proposed, and included a copy of Homer’s <i>Iliad</i> and a work of the Attic tragedian Euripides. <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/1042"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1042</a>, l. 48, also contains a fragmentary reference to these book dedications, as does <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/1040"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1040</a> (100 books, "in accordance with the decree"). Cf. Pélékidis, 263-64; Haake, 45.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-6"><a href="#ref-6">[6]</a> On the officials responsible for proclamations in these decrees see <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/1043-with-add-p-671"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1043</a>, n. 5.</span>
            </div>
            

